node.text:
4 DAYS UNTIL SELFHEALERS CIRCLE ENROLLMENT 🎉

Thanks to member feedback, we’ve spent the past year building our own hosting platform. It’s easier to navigate + we now have a private community outside of facebook. Members are loving our new space.

The cost is $26/month or $286/year (one month free). My goal has always been to make the Circle affordable + accessible.

Enrollment will open January 1st at 12pm PST. Spaces are limited + do SELL OUT quickly. If you’re on the waitlist, you’ll be sent a link a few moments before enrollment opens. It might be helpful to set an alarm. There are currently 30,000+ people on the waitlist.

To find complete details on what the circle is all about, click the link in my bio. You can also add yourself to the waitlist.

I’ll see you in the ⭕️ + cannot wait for your healing journey to begin! selfhealers

node.text: Today it’s a true honor to talk to @dr.editheger— I’m actually a bit overwhelmed post filming this. Edith is a psychologist + Holocaust survivor who just released the book “The Gift.” I got chills throughout the book + know members of this community will love every word. Edith is an embodied teacher who gifts us with the wisdom that we are not not victims of our past, but powerful creators of our future. Her story is a testament to our true human potential. She’s a gift. I hope you all enjoy #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The Fight Trauma Response: Temper that is very explosive unpredictable @the.holistic.psychologist 2. Taunts, mocks, insults, shames 3. "My way or the highway" tendency to need the final say ignores other perspectives 4. Yells, slams doors, screams, becomes aggressive 5. Easily becomes reactive (can confuse people with their 'big" emotions) 6. Always feels as though they're being threatened, will protect self at any cost .Often feels shameful/remorseful post outburst'.

node.text:
The fight trauma response often presents as explosive, unpredictable, + seemingly “out of nowhere.”

The fight trauma response can be very scary for the person experiencing it as well as everyone around them.

When in fight, the body is prepared to do just that: fight. There’s aggression, mocking, shaming + the main objective is to stop the threat.

People who go into fight will do anything to stop the threat which is why the fight response is common in narcism or what’s called “sociopath” behavior.  Self preservation comes before everything which can bring out some pretty extreme or troubling behavior.

People who go into fight often confuse people around them. They can be seemingly “find” + turn on a dime. It can also look like they’re overreacting (which is important to understand that internally they’re not reacting to the present moment— they’re reacting to the past).

That’s the foundation of a trauma response.

Many people who go into fight were abused, belittled, or completely ignored/neglected + unconsciously their core motive is to never experience that pain again. Any attention is good attention.

There is often a cycle of deep shame after fight. When people “come too” (most dissociate during outbursts) they feel extreme guilt or shame. Sometimes to avoid this they “pretend everything” is ok. They expect the family to quickly bounce back + forget about the events.

If you grew up in a home with a parent figure who frequently went into fight, you might have become incredibly good at acting as if everything is ok when it’s not.

HEALING LOOKS LIKE:
- engaging in high intensity (quick) exercise to remove aggressive energy 

- learning to feel anger (anger is a “cover” emotion for deep sadness + fear) it gives a false sense of control. Learning to pause + allow yourself to feel the sadness takes practice.

- learn PAUSE: neural pathways have been formed to knee jerk anger. Practicing pause + removing yourself will help to re-wire the brain 

- write your inner child a letter about your anger + the pain that builds inside you. Let it flow. Inside every person dealing with flight is a *very* hurt inner child 

Do you go into fight? #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The Flight Trauma Response: 1. Chronic rushing or "always going" 2. Feels uncomfortable (or even panic when still 3. Energy spent micromanaging people + situations around them 4. Has a history of abruptly ending relationships or phobic of commitment 5. Feels trapped easily 6. Makes plan to avoid any downtime or throws themselves in to work/achievement 7. Often presents as anxiety or panic attacks'.

node.text:
The flight trauma response is an adaptive coping mechanism that we learn as children when our environment isn’t fully safe.

When our environment isn’t safe or predictable, we learn to adapt by becoming hyper vigilant to the environment to see when we might leave.

If our parent figures had explosive tempers, were chaotic, or were emotionally absent we unconsciously learn life is not safe.” Because life is not safe, we create coping mechanisms that allow us to avoid life. Or leave it on a moments notice.

I’ve worked with many workaholics or overachievers who’s flight trauma response is often rewarded or validated. Yet inside they’re resentful, burnt out, + usually disillusioned with their work. At the same time, they need that work (+ it’s sometimes dysfunctional climate) to feel at home.

When it comes to relationships, they tend to have “one foot out the door” or always bring up ending or leaving as self protection. 

Many times being stuck in a flight trauma response is misdiagnosed as social anxiety or any kind of chronic anxiety. It can also cause panic attacks.

Healing is about teaching the body safety within stillness + the present moment 

THIS LOOKS LIKE:

1. Spending a few minutes each morning in stillness, meditation, or journaling. A great mantra: “I am safe to be still”

2. Turning down an invite while also NOT making another plan (like doing chores or running errands)

3. Taking time to journal *your* own values + beliefs (this might be hard especially if you’ve never practiced— just focus on the things that you feel are important for you) 

4. Letting your partner in on this trauma response + how it presents (for example: when I get scared, I tend to flee or self isolate + could use your reassurance)

5. Movement— the body is dealing with adrenaline + cortisol + need an outlet that feels good for you.

Flight is a pattern. There’s nothing bad or wrong with it— it’s simply revealing conditioning. 

Do you have a flight trauma response? #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The Freeze Trauma Response: @the.holistic.psychologist 1.Feeling completely numb, life is "pointless" 2. Shutdown silent treatment, complete avoidance) 3. Hiding out from the world 4. Procrastination or inability to make even small decisions 5. Endless social media scrolling/binge tv watching 6. Confusion over whats real or unreal (or actually happening) 7. Often confused/misdiagnosed with depression'.

node.text:
The freeze trauma response is often (long term) confused or misdiagnosed as depression. 

Freeze is a coping mechanism adopted in childhood to survive painful or overwhelming childhoods. 

We learn to shut down or completely avoid anything where we would be seen or anything outside of our comfort zone. 

We don’t feel a desire to connect with others or have an overall belief that life is pointless or meaningless.

We may “hide out” from the world. Or when extremely activated, we black out or forget entire moments/years of our lives.

Healing from freeze involves returning to the body. And finding safety within the present moment.

THIS LOOKS LIKE:
- practicing breathwork or movement in small amounts daily 

- learning to focus on the sensations within the body without assigning a judgement to them (just feeling for 10-20 seconds then identifying the sensation (this feels like tingling, this feels like heat)

- finding community around your true passions (no matter how other people feel about them or have judged these passions) online support groups can be helpful here

- celebrating small victories like taking a small walk to the mailbox, completing one small task, or doing one thing outside your comfort zone (like making a meal you’ve never tried.

Do you freeze? #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The Fawn Trauma Response: 1.People-pleasing @the.holistic.psychologist 2. Going along with another berson' perspective, beliefs, or values without connecting with your own 3. Dissociating (leaving the body) "spacing out" 4. Lets other people make decisions 5. Avoids any situation that could lead to conflict 6. Fears saying "no" 7. Overly polite agreeable 8. Hyper aware of other people's emotions +needs while betraying your own'.

node.text:
The fawn trauma response is an adaptive coping mechanism that we learn as children when our environment isn’t fully safe.

When our environment isn’t safe or predictable, we learn to adapt by dismissing our own needs + focusing on the needs of others.

If our parent figures had explosive tempers, were chaotic, or were emotionally absent we unconsciously learn to be “easy.” To people please + avoid any conflict. Many people who fawn become chronically distracted with what other people think about them because there was a time in childhood where the emotional climate of the home was determined by someone outside of themselves.

An easy way to learn if you cope by fawning us to see how comfortable you are with boundaries. If they made you cringe, make you feel super guilty or afraid— that’s a good sign you fawn

Healing is about making small steps outside of your comfort zone to create confidence.

THIS LOOKS LIKE:

1. Stating a small boundary to someone you feel comfortable with

2. Turning down an invite without over explaining or over apologizing 

3. Taking time to journal *your* own values + beliefs (this might be hard especially if you’ve never practiced— just focus on the things that you feel are important for you)

4. Letting someone know how they made you feel (also will be scary— take time to pause + breathe. You might feel safer writing this than speaking it)

5. Standing up for your own perspective “I see why you feel that way, I see this differently” “We disagree on this, + that’s ok” 

Fawning is a pattern. There’s nothing bad or wrong with it— it’s simply revealing conditioning. 

Do you fawn? #selfhealers

Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on September 11, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Every time we blame someone for our current circumstances, we miss an opportunity to create new ones @the.holistic.psychologist'.

node.text:
Blame is so seductive to our ego. 

If we blame someone else for our circumstances we get to do two things:

1. Avoid shifting or changing our habits + patterns (stay safe)

2. Avoid feeling our own pain + facing parts of ourselves that we don’t want to see (stay safe)

The egos primary focus is to keep us safe. 

This means keeping us in familiar patterns that we know the outcome— even if that outcome has us feeling miserable. Or suffering every day.

In order to create the life we want to live, we have to release our strong tendency to blame. This in itself is healing. 

This doesn’t mean we deny that other people have deeply hurt us. Or, that events that have occurred within our lives have created coping mechanisms + reactions that live in our mind + body. 

One of the most common questions I get is: “Don’t you think that teaching about family dynamics or the impact of the parent-child relationship creates parent blaming?”

My answer is: no. Unless you want it to.

There is a big difference between AWARENESS + BLAME.

Awareness holds space for acceptance. 

It says: I see this. This occurred. This lives within me. I exist this way because of these events + their impact on my perspective. My nervous system carries these events. 

Blame subtly gives away our power + disconnects us from the truth of who we are.

Blame says: I can’t do “x” because of you. If I didn’t experience this, I would be better. I can’t change because of this. My life is your responsibility. Who I am + how I experience life is not within my own hands.

There’s nothing wrong with blame. We all go through periods of blame + the intense emotions that come with it. It’s a stage in the grief process.

Getting stuck within blame— allowing blame to be our identity is when we can lose ourselves in the process. Healing is recovering ourselves. 

What are your experiences around blame #selfhealers

node.text:
Relationships are our teachers.

If we are willing to be the objective witness, the dynamics within our relationships give us major awareness of our conditioning.

Secure friendships means there is a secure attachment between two people.

Many of us never witnessed (or had) secure, safe attachments as children.

So we unconsciously create friendships that mirror our earliest trauma bonds.

Trauma bonds are insecure relationships. Where we feel fear of criticism, of being abandoned, or fear taking space/having clear boundaries.

Unlearning these dynamics is part of the lifelong journey of healing.

Secure friendships encourage mutual evolution. They allow for difficult conversations. They allow for different perspectives without condemnation or judgment. They seek true connection, not ego-based bonding.

There’s trust + a clear knowing that you both seek to celebrate each other’s true, core authentic self.

Tag a friend who’s doing this work + let them know you see them #selfhealers

node.text:
Last night I watched L Word Mississippi which is a show that documents the life of gay women in the south who are not accepted by their church, family, + community.

It reminded me just how much we are truly wired to need each other. And how painful it is when people don’t accept parts of who we are. Or, when they shame us for who we are.

To understand human behavior is to understand that in order to accept others, we must have self acceptance. The harsh truth is many of us struggle to accept parts of who we are— we’ve had parents, peers, teachers, + society label those parts of who we are as “bad.” This is when we unconsciously learn to hide parts of ourselves. 

The more we’ve hidden (repressed) the more critical we become of those who express parts of themselves that make us uncomfortable.

With religious conditioning there’s an extra fear element of: hell, condemnation, or never ending judgment. Which, when repeated in childhood over + over again because a mental reality that’s incredibly difficult to escape from.

We are a collective that is struggling deeply with accepting all parts of self. We don’t like to face the truth of our shadow: that we all feel anger, rage, jealousy, unworthiness. That while there is endless good within us, there is also fear. Where there is fear there is shame. 

Where there is shame, we tend to project onto other people.

PEOPLE WHO ACCEPT THEMSELVES FULLY CAN:

- accept (even celebrate) differences in others 

- understand outside perspectives without shaming them or using them to bolster their own ego 

- sit with uncomfortable emotions, ask questions, be curious

- come to their own conclusions, without following a mental (or ideological) frame work created by another person 

- understand human nature is to grow + evolve which means accepting other people’s unique journey 

- be kind to themselves when they do judge others 

So often we take other people’s actions personally + that’s a normal human reaction. It hurts when people don’t see us or don’t accept us.

When we look beyond the ego, we can see these people are deeply struggling with their own lack of self acceptance #selfhealers

node.text:
Emotional addiction is so common, most of us are unaware that we’re in this cycle.

I know I was. And often still am.

Our emotions are valid, important messengers.

Most of us were not taught how to regulate our emotions. Most of us were conditioned in homes where chaos was present + adults existed within a daily emotional roller coaster. 

Meaning, all decisions + behaviors were run by emotional states. This will manifest as: impulsive decision making, anger, constant distraction, + daily exhaustion where sleep doesn’t feel rejuvenating.

Emotions are a mind + body experience. Our primal “survival brain” is activated. Cortisol + adrenaline are released. Emotional states become memorized by the body + we unconsciously seek them.

Understanding why we seek certain situations can allow us to relieve shame. Becoming aware of how we do this allows us to teach our mind + body new emotional states of wellness like peace, safety, + connection.

“I’m bored” was my favorite saying in childhood. What I would come to understand as an adult, was that heightened emotional states of fear had become exciting to me. I learned that in these states, my family was connected. With the hormonal response happening within me, I felt like myself.

I began healing through asking myself “why.” Why did I want to reach out to that person? Why do I want to watch this news story? Why do I seek relationships where I feel ‘love’ within a cycle of emotional abandonment? Why do my friendships mostly exist as mutual complaining? Why does venting feel so good?

Notice. Without judgment. Start asking why.

Peace is a practice. Peace is a consistent choice of self care #selfhealers

node.text:
Most of us are emotionally immature because we were not modeled: how to regulate our emotions, how to get our needs met, + how to hold space for other people’s emotions without blaming, shaming or advice giving.

Becoming emotionally mature is a practice.

And it starts with learning how to be safe in your own body. How to witness your own emotions (without reacting to them). And, how to allow another persons emotional state without taking it on or reject it all together.

It’s a beautiful thing to practice this in a relationship. 

Who’s learning how to be an emotionally mature partner? #selfhealers
